  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate the function \\( f(x) = a^x \\) with respect to \\( x \\), we can use the chain rule. Here, \\( a \\) is a constant and \\( x \\) is the variable. The differentiation of \\( a^x \\) involves the natural logarithm of \\( a \\).\n\nFirst, let's find the first derivative:\n\n\\[ f'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x) \\]\n\nUsing the chain rule, we get:\n\n\\[ f'(x) = a^x \\cdot \\ln(a) \\]\n\nNow, let's proceed to find the higher-order derivatives up to the fourth term.\n\nSecond derivative:\n\n\\[ f''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x \\cdot \\ln(a)) \\]\n\\[ f''(x) = \\ln(a) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x) \\]\n\\[ f''(x) = \\ln(a) \\cdot a^x \\cdot \\ln(a) \\]\n\\[ f''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^2 \\]\n\nThird derivative:\n\n\\[ f'''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^2) \\]\n\\[ f'''(x) = (\\ln(a))^2 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x) \\]\n\\[ f'''(x) = (\\ln(a))^2 \\cdot a^x \\cdot \\ln(a) \\]\n\\[ f'''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^3 \\]\n\nFourth derivative:\n\n\\[ f''''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^3) \\]\n\\[ f''''(x) = (\\ln(a))^3 \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x) \\]\n\\[ f''''(x) = (\\ln(a))^3 \\cdot a^x \\cdot \\ln(a) \\]\n\\[ f''''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^4 \\]\n\nSo, the derivatives of \\( a^x \\) up to the fourth term are:\n\n1. First derivative: \\( f'(x) = a^x \\cdot \\ln(a) \\)\n2. Second derivative: \\( f''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^2 \\)\n3. Third derivative: \\( f'''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^3 \\)\n4. Fourth derivative: \\( f''''(x) = a^x \\cdot (\\ln(a))^4 \\)",
